FOOT & MOUTH DISEASE - CHINA (15)
*********************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>
Sponsored in part by Elsevier, publisher of
Health Information for International Travel 2005-2006
<http://thelancet.url123.com/an9m7>
[1]
Date: Sat, 31 Dec 2005
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Shanghai Daily, 31 Dec 2005 [edited]
<http://www.shanghaidaily.com>

Starting 6 Dec 2005, some cattle on a Changqing District farm began
suffering from fevers and poor appetites. By Sunday, 25 Dec 2005, the
number of ill cattle on the farm grew to 48.
On Mon 26 Dec 2005 the provincial veterinary authority initially
attributed the mass illness to the Asian type 1 foot-and-mouth
disease [FMD].
A state FMD lab confirmed the diagnosis on Thu, 29 Dec 2005,
according to the ministry report. The ministry said authorities
culled the 48 cattle and another 43 raised in the same herd.
In spring [2005], China restricted the FMD Asia 1 outbreaks to 5
provincial regions: Beijing, its neighboring province of Hebei,
eastern China's Shandong and Jiangsu provinces, and northwestern
Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region. [See an interactive administrative
map of China at:
<http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/2003-04/03/content_815413.htm>].
The disease was reported on 2 cow farms in Tai'an City, Shandong and
Jiangsu's Wuxi City in early April 2005.
Early in May, local veterinary authorities also confirmed the
outbreak in the Hoboksar area of Xinjiang, Yanqing County of Beijing
and Hebei's Sanhe City.
By late May, medical workers had culled about 4000 cattle across the
country, mostly cows. For each culled animal, the central and local
governments offer compensation ranging from 4000 yuan (USD 496) to
6000 yuan (USD 744), according to the ministry.
FMD is a highly contagious degenerative viral disease attacking
cattle, pigs and other cloven-hoofed animals. It is not considered
dangerous to humans.
--
